   <h1>Re: [T2] WARNING!!!! (related to Steering box)</h1>
   <b>Old Volks Home <oldvolkshome(-at-)gmail.com></b><br/>
   <i>2010-03-03 00:01:38+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>Chris -

I've passed along your concerns to Euromax's owner, of whom I have known for
a long time and he appreciates feedback of this kinda stuff.  Euromax is one
of the main and largest importing agents located in Florida that distributes
their products to ALL of the main warehouse distributors in the USA, which
in turn supplies most if not all the on-line vendors (including Airhead
Parts/VWG).  Once he gets the pmail and knowing him he will definitely look
into the problem and do additional tests to check it's quality.  Euromax may
not be the actual manufacturer, but is probably the main purchaser (perhaps
exclusively) from the factory in Brazil.

Unfortunately, there is no supplier of the OE German coupler discs, they
seem to have dried up as a supply in the past couple of years.  So the
Brazlian made coupler disc may (for the moment) be the only replacement.

At Airhead/VWG, we've sold hundreds of these Euromax supplied coupler discs
without this kind of problem being reported, but I've alerted the sales
department of your post.
-- 
Jim Thompson
84 GL 1.9 "Gloria"
84 Westfalia 2.1 "Ole Putt"
72 411 Station Wagon "Pug"
Full Timing Since March 1999
oldvolkshome(-at-)gmail.com
http://www.oldvolkshome.com
***********************************
On Tue, Mar 2, 2010 at 3:24 PM, Chris Slaymaker  wrote:

> I poster earlier about a questionable defective steering box.  I
> mentioned that it seemed that there was too much back-and-forth play
> in the axis of the input shaft/steering column.  What alerted me to
> the problem was that the bolts that mount the steering coupling were
> starting to wear through the bell-shaped cover plate seen here:
> http://www.thesamba.com/vw/forum/album_page.php?pic_id=652585
> .  What I ultimately found was that the steering coupling was BUCKLING
> under conditions of torque greater than 30 ft-lbs.  The steering
> coupling would twist under that much torque and buckle, sending the
> steering column up into the cabin as much has 3 centimeters.
> In my opinion, this is setting up for CATASTROPHIC FAILURE.  I bought
> the steering coupling from one of our online vendors   It is
> manufactured by a company called Euromax, which is apparently based in
> Brazil.  I hope this is just a singular incident, but PLEASE check to
> make sure this is not happening to you!!!
> Chris Slaymaker
> 1971 Westfalia "Lurch"
> 1971 Squareback "Foster"
> Knoxville, TN</pre>


